<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05171i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05171i">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05171i"> 171(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> favourite place of sepulture</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Looking around him in that great cemetery <font color="green">[at the ruins of the Seven Churches at Clonmacnoise]</font> he <font color="green">[Petrie]</font> was the first to recognise to what an extent it was filled with inscribed monuments, recording the names of distinguished persons who had been buried there in former times. It was a <mark>favourite place of sepulchre</mark> for kings and chiefs, for bishops and abbots, for men of piety and learning, from the sixth to the twelfth century. <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) (George Petrie) 214-5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
